default6default.0default              defaultthe relative advantages and disadvantages of the proposed levy rather than a possible complete ban on lightweight plastic bagsdefault6
default.1
default              
defaultThe proposed levy exempts biodegradable bags. By offering a free bag
default,
default it would continue to encourage a ‘use once’ mentality as there would 
defaultbe 
defaultlittle incentive to remember to reuse bags. Consumers would also view the bag as a more sustainable solution to plastic, despite it not being suitable for recycling nor would it change consumers’ behaviour 
defaultregarding 
defaultdisposal.
default6
default.2
default              
defaultFrom WRAP’s own report and LCA data, all bags should be reused as many times as possible. Biodegradable bags especially paper bags have very limited reuse opportunities.
default&#xa0;
default7default.0default              defaultthe rationale for excluding particular types of retailer from the levy schemedefault7
default.1
default              
defaultIf the rationale for the plastic bag charge
default 
defaultis environmental, then its aim should be to change consumer behaviour and to encourage the reuse of bags as many times as possible.  This would not be achieved if some retailers were exempt.
default7
default.2
default              
defaultExcluding some retailers would send out conflicting messages to consumers and could therefore affect the potential benefits from the charge in other areas.
default&#xa0;
default8default.0default              defaultthe lessons to be learnt from other countries’ experiences in this areadefault8
default.1
default              
default              
defaultIn Wales, consumers have adapted to the charge and reusing bags is commonplace as in Europe. 
default9default.0default              defaultAny social or economic impacts of the proposed bag levy, for example on affordability for particular households or businessesdefault9
default.1
default              
defaultThere would be an enormous loss of potential funds available to charities as a result of the exemption of biodegradable bags.  In Wales, the proceeds from the 5p charge go towards social and environmental good causes. With the potential volumes available, charities stand to lose considerable funds as few retailers w
defaultould offer a plastic bag for 5p.
default 
default M
defaultost retailers will want to be as competitive as possible and therefore most will offer a free bio
defaultdegradable
default bag. If a charge was imposed on all single use bags as in Wales, the proceeds could be redirected into research and development to improve kerbside recycling/on the go recycling where the main problem lies.
default10.0default              defaultAny defaulthygiene impacts or wider health impactsdefault10
default.1
default              
defaultWe are not aware of any health implications of a biodegradable or 
defaultoxo
default degradable bag. 
